\backslash
section*{Chapter 17:
 The Java Bridge}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

One of Scalaâ€™s greatest strengths is its "Zero-Overhead" interoperability with Java.
 You don't need a wrapper,
 a foreign function interface (FFI),
 or a translation layer.
 To Scala,
 a Java class is just another type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Is it Necessary?}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Technically,
 no.
 Scala can do everything Java can do (and usually more concisely).
 However,
 it is 
\backslash
textbf{strategically vital} because it gives you instant access to 25 years of JVM libraries.
 If there isn't a Scala-specific library for a task,
 you can use the Java one without a second thought.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Using Java from Scala}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Using a Java library in Scala is transparent.
 You import it and call it exactly like Scala code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

// Using the standard Java Time API inside Scala
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

import java.time.LocalDateTime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

val now = LocalDateTime.now()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

val formatted = now.format(DateTimeFormatter.ISO_DATE)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Extending Scala with Java Classes}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Sometimes you might want to write a high-performance routine in Java or use a Java-based framework that requires you to extend its classes.
 Scala handles this effortlessly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

// A Scala class extending a Java Base Class
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

class MyServlet extends javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  override def doGet(req:
 HttpServletRequest,
 resp:
 HttpServletResponse):
 Unit =
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    resp.getWriter.write("Hello from Scala via Java Servlet!")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{The "Pragmatic" Conversion:
 Java Converters}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

The only "friction" between the two is in the Collection libraries (e.g.,
 a 
\backslash
texttt{java.util.List} is not the same as a Scala 
\backslash
texttt{List}).
 Fortunately,
 Scala provides a bridge to convert them automatically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

import scala.jdk.CollectionConverters.*
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

val javaList = new java.util.ArrayList[String]()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

javaList.add("Java Item")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

// Convert to a Scala-friendly Buffer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

val scalaList = javaList.asScala
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

