\backslash
subsection*{When to Write Java}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

You might choose to write a portion of your project in Java if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{itemize}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    
\backslash
item 
\backslash
textbf{Team Skills}:
 You have a legacy team that knows Java intimately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    
\backslash
item 
\backslash
textbf{Micro-Optimizations}:
 In extremely rare cases,
 the way Java handles certain low-level arrays can be slightly more predictable for the JIT compiler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    
\backslash
item 
\backslash
textbf{Framework Requirements}:
 Some older Java frameworks use heavy "Reflection" that is occasionally easier to satisfy with a small Java "stub" class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

